roaches and how they relate to the classical idea of public administration as a design science. Contributors consider the potential, challenges and applications of design approaches and distinguish between three methods currently characterising the discipline: design as optimisation, design as exploration and design as co-creation. Developing the dialogue around public administration as a design science, this collection explores how a more ‘designerly’ way of thinking can improve public administration and public policy. The articles on which Chapters 4, 5 and 6 are based are available Open Access under CC-BY-NC licence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBekkers, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlomkamp, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorkowska-Waszak, Sylwia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryson, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrosby, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Jong, Jorrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomaradzka, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroenleer, Martijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuy Peters, B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermus, Margot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowlett, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Jenny M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aM. Lewis, Jenny, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGann, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4h